children.name: Sovereign Territory: Territory that a sovereign state exercises exclusive jurisdiction over.
Region (Administrative region, Cultural region, Geographical region)
Spiral Bend (also known as Helix Bend)
Brackish Water Estuaries (or Partially Mixed Estuaries)
Salt Lake Beds (or Saline Lake Beds)
Freshwater Lake Beds (or Freshwater Lake Plains)
Alkaline Lake Beds (or Soda Lake Beds)
Volcano Crater Lake Subclass (also known as Maar and Phreatic Crater Lakes)
Endorheic Intermittent Salt Lakes (e.g., Great Salt Lake in Utah)
Orographic Intermittent Salt Lakes (e.g., Tanganyika Njila in Tanzania)
Playa Intermittent Salt Lakes (e.g., Owens Lake in California)
Perennial Intermittent Ponds: These are ponds that typically have water year-round but may dry up during prolonged periods of drought.

Seasonal Intermittent Ponds: These ponds have water for part of the year, usually during a specific season like spring or summer, and dry up at other times. They may refill due to snowmelt or rainfall.
Solar Evaporation Salt Ponds (or Solar Salterns)
Platform Reefs (optional, as it's a type of platform coral reef system)
Sand Shoals (also known as Bar Shoals)
Cyclic Intermittent Stream (also known as Periodic Intermittent Stream)
Multiple Mouths: A stream with more than two primary outlets or openings.
Surface Irrigation Systems: These include basin irrigation, border strip, furrow, and flood systems.
Gravity-flow Irrigation Systems: Examples are canal, contour ditch, and gravity tank systems.
Pressure (Pump-Driven) Irrigation Systems: This includes sprinkler, drip, micro-irrigation, and center pivot systems.
Borehole Wells (also known as Drilled Wells)
Freshwater Waterholes (e.g., lakes, ponds, and springs)
Saltwater Waterholes (e.g., estuaries, bays, and oceans)
Artificial Waterholes (e.g., reservoirs, dams, and wells)
Running Waters (Streams): Rapids, Rills, Brooks, Rivers
Standing Waters (Lakes): Ponds, Reservoirs, Tarns, Lochs
Lochs (This is a specific type of lake found in Scotland)
Mixed Agricultural Colony (includes both settlers and state management)
Antarctica (often considered a continent but not inhabited)
Recreational Parks (Playgrounds, Sports Parks, Picnic Parks)
Ungulate Reserves (for species like deer, elk, antelope)
Alpine Lake Region (or High-altitude Lake Region)
Riverine Scenic Areas (Can also be Forested Scenic Areas, depending on the dominating vegetation)
Recreational Attractions: Theme parks, zoos, aquariums, amusement parks, water parks, and adventure sports facilities providing entertainment and leisure activities for tourists.
Green Spaces (Parks, Gardens, etc.) within Cities and Towns.
Urban Parks: Open spaces created primarily for public recreation and leisure activities, often including facilities such as playgrounds, sports fields, picnic areas, and walking trails.
Public Green Spaces (Squares & Plazas): Open, landscaped urban spaces designed primarily for social interaction and public events, often located at the center of cities or towns.
seat of a first-order administrative division
seat of a second-order administrative division
seat of a third-order administrative division
seat of a fourth-order administrative division
seat of a fifth-order administrative division
historical capital of a political entity
Mixed Farm Village (combination of arable and livestock farming)
seat of government of a political entity
Ghost Towns: Abandoned towns that were once inhabited but are now vacant.
Persian Royal Roads (Royal Roads of the Achaemenid Empire)
Animal Facilities (e.g., dairy farms, poultry farms, livestock farms)
Crop Production Facilities (e.g., greenhouses, field crops, orchards)
Artificial Burial Caves: Created by humans for burial purposes, often found in ancient civilizations like the Mayans and Egyptians.
Open Labor Camps (Temporary and Seasonal Workers)
Unconventional Oil Camp (UOC) (includes Shale Oil, Oil Sands, and Coalbed Methane Camps)
Loose Corrals (also known as Grazing Corrals)
Embankment Dam (Roller Compacted Concrete, Earthfill, Rockfill)
Diplomatic Office: Any premises used by a diplomat for the purpose of performing their official duties.
Arable Farm (Cereal, Vegetable, and Oilseed Farms)
Livestock Farm (Dairy, Poultry, and Swine Farms)
Mixed Farms (Combination of Crop and Animal Production)
Natural Sciences Research Institutes (Physics, Chemistry, Biology, Mathematics)
Mutex Locks (Mutex is a short form for mutual exclusion)
Read-Write Locks (Read-write semaphore or RW lock)
Jet Mill (also known as Air Classifying Mill)
Hard rock mines (specific to gold hard rock deposits)
Placer mines (specific to gold placer deposits)
Solution Mining (Solvent Extraction – Electrowinning, or SX-EW) of Copper Mines
Placer Iron Mines (rare, but exist for deposits in riverbeds or near stream beds)
Potash and Sodium Chloride Mines (Used in fertilizers and chemical industries)
Sufi Mosques (also known as Tariqa Mosques)
Monastic Scholars (focuses on study and intellectual pursuits within the monastery)
Monastic Guardians (responsible for protecting the monastery and its inhabitants)
Synthesis Radio Telescopes (e.g., Very Large Array, Lovell Telescope)
Single-Dish Radio Telescopes (e.g., Parkes Observatory, Arecibo Observatory)
Radio Interferometry Networks (e.g., Atacama Large Millimeter/submillimeter Array, Square Kilometre Array)
Off-Street Parking Lots (includes garages, private lots)
Surface Water Intake and Transfer Stations
Sphenoconic Pyramid (Pyramid with a quadrilateral base)
Square-Based Pyramid (Pyramid with a square base)
Mixed Ranch (Combining different livestock and crops)
Game Ranch (For breeding and raising wild game species)
Yard Siding: Used for storing, sorting, and assembling trains in a rail yard.
Maintenance Siding: Allows for the repair and maintenance of trains without disrupting regular service on the main tracks.
Mental Health Sanatorium (for patients with mental health issues)
Tropical Sanatorium (for patients suffering from tropical diseases)
Unit Square (often denoted as 'a x a' squares)
Right-angled Square (consists of four right angles)
Square with Diagonal (contains two perpendicular diagonals)
Forestry and Natural Resources Experiment Station
Home Economics Experiment Station (or Family and Consumer Sciences Experiment Station)
Floating Whaling Station (or Flensing Factory Ship)
Companion Animal Veterinary Facilities (e.g., clinics, hospitals, shelters for dogs and cats)
Livestock Veterinary Facilities (e.g., farms, ranches, dairies)
Specialty Crops Farms (e.g., Spices, Nuts, Tea)
High-energy Beach (includes surf beaches and windy beaches)
Low-energy Beach (includes calm, sandy beaches with shallow waters)
Rocky Shore Beach (includes rocky coastlines with intertidal zones)
Resurgence Canyons (or Collapsed Lava Tube Canyons)
Cone (Spherical): Defined in spherical coordinates with a base radius, height, and polar angle θ.
Meteorite Craters (a specific type of impact crater)
Type I Meander Neck (also known as Reversed S-shaped meander)
Type II Meander Neck (also known as Classic S-shaped meander)
Type III Meander Neck (also known as Z-shaped or Wickham's meander)
Kinsky Peninsula (a region in Siberia, Russia)
Angular Escarpments (Detachment, Normal, Reverse, Recumbent-slide escarpments)
Intertidal Zone (also known as Tidal Shore)

Hydrological Interdune Trough: These are lower lying areas within dunes that collect water during rain events or snowmelt, playing a crucial role in groundwater recharge and supporting various ecosystems.
Intermontane Valleys (e.g., Basin and Range Provinces, Rift valleys)
Canyon Valleys (e.g., Grand Canyon, Yarlung Tsangpo Grand Canyon)
Alpine Valleys (Valley type characterized by high mountains and steep slopes)
Fluvial Valleys (Valleys formed by rivers and streams)
Alpine - Mountain (high, steep and dramatic peaks with extensive glaciers)

Alpine High Mountains: These are the highest parts of the Alps, characterized by extremely high elevations and permanent snow cover. Examples include Mont Blanc, the Matterhorn, and the Bernina Range.

Glacier Alpine Mountains: These areas are characterized by extensive glaciation. The Swiss Alps, Norwegian mountains, and Scandinavian mountains fall under this category due to their high concentration of glaciers.
Foothill - Hill (lower slope of a mountain range)
Foothill Plains: Flat or gently sloping land at the base of a mountain range.
Foothill Forests: Forested areas found on the lower slopes of a mountain range.
Foothill Grasslands: Areas with grasses and other low-lying vegetation on the lower slopes of a mountain range.
Peak - Mountain (the highest point of a landform)
Ridge - Mountain (long, narrow elevated landform with sides of approximately equal height)
Spur and Bennett Spur (subclass of Backbone Ridge)
Slope - Hill or Mountain (inclined ground or surface)
Summit - Mountain (highest point on a mountain or hill)
Peak - The highest point of a specific mountain or hill.
Summit Ridge - A continuous elevated portion extending along the highest part of a mountain or range.
Valley - Lowland between mountains or hills
Canyon Valleys (e.g., Yosemite Valley, Grand Canyon)
Temperate Deciduous Forest (e.g., Eastern U.S. Deciduous Forest)
Tropical Scrublands (Thorn Scrub, Xerophytic Scrub, etc.)
Mountain Tundra (also known as Northern Forest-Tundra or Taiga Tundra)
White Wine Vineyards (Chardonnay, Sauvignon Blanc, Riesling)
Temperate Coastal Rainforests (e.g., Sitka Spruce - Picea sitchensis)
Tropical and Subtropical Coastal Forests (e.g., Mangrove-Dry Forest ecotone, Mangrove-Monsoon Forest ecotone)
Physical Geonames (Physical features: mountains, rivers, islands)
Anthropogenic Geonames (Cities, towns, buildings, man-made structures)
Statues: Apex Statue, Memorial Statue, Sculpture Garden Statue
Monuments: National Monument, War Memorial, Commemorative Monument
Skyscrapers: Iconic Skyscraper, Tallest Building, Landmark Skyscraper
